.TH ROGUE 6 "Mar 18, 2026"
.UC 4
.SH NAME
rogue \- Exploring The Dungeons of Doom \- version 5.4.5
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B @PROGRAM@
[
.B \-s
[
.I score_flle
]
]
[
.B \-d
]
[
.B \-V
]
[
.B \-r
]
[
.I save_file
]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
.I Rogue
is a computer fantasy game with a new twist.  It is CRT oriented and the
object of the game is to survive the attacks of various monsters and get
a lot of gold, rather than the puzzle solving orientation of most computer
fantasy games.
.PP
To get started you really only need to know two commands.  The command
.B ?
will give you a list of the available commands and the command
.B /
will identify the things you see on the screen.
.PP
To win the game (as opposed to merely playing to beat other people's high
scores) you must locate the Amulet of Yendor which is somewhere below
the 20th level of the dungeon and get it out.  Nobody has achieved this
yet and if somebody does, they will probably go down in history as a hero
among heroes.
.PP
When the game ends, either by your death, when you quit, or if you (by
some miracle) manage to win,
.I rogue
will give you a list of the top scorers.  The scoring is based entirely
upon how much gold you get.  There is a 10% penalty for getting yourself
killed.
.PP
If
.I save_file
is specified,
rogue will be restored from the specified saved game file.
If the
.B \-r
option is used, the save game file is presumed to be the default.
.PP
The
.B \-s
option will print out the list of scores from the default score file.
.PP
The
.BR \-s \ score_file
option will print out the list of scores from the given
.IR score_file .
.PP
The
.B \-d
option will kill you and try to add you to the score file.
.PP
The
.B \-V
will print the rogue version, release date,
and then exit.
.PP
For more detailed directions, read the
.B README.md
file of the rogue5.4 GitHub repo:
.PP
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#rogue-54
.in -0.5i
.SH OPTIONS
The
.B rogue
game options may be displayed and changed by using the
.B o
command.
.PP
The option names are:
.PP
.TP
.B terse / noterse
.sp
Useful for those who are tired of the sometimes lengthy messages of rogue.
.sp
This is a useful option to enable when playing on an historically slow terminal.
.sp
Default:
.B noterse
.sp
Recommendation:
.B noterse
.PP
.TP
.B flush / noflush
.sp
If this option is set, typeahead is thrown away after each round of battle.
.sp
This is useful for those who type far ahead, and then watch in dismay as a Bat kills them.
.sp
Default:
.B noflush
.sp
Recommendation:
.B flush
.TP
.B jump / nojump
.sp
If this option is set, running moves will not be displayed until you reach the end of the move.
.sp
This is a useful option to enable when playing on an historically slow terminal.
.sp
Default:
.B nojump
.sp
Recommendation:
.B jump
.TP
.B seefloor / noseefloor
.sp
Display the floor around you on the screen as you move through dark rooms.
.sp
This is a useful option to disable when playing on an historically slow terminal.
.sp
Default:
.B seefloor
.sp
Recommendation:
.B seefloor
.TP
.B passgo / nopassgo
.sp
Follow turnings in passageways.
If you run in a passage and you run into stone or a wall, rogue will see if it can turn to the right or left.
If it can only turn one way, it will turn that way. If it can turn either or neither, it will stop.
.sp
This algorithm can sometimes lead to slightly confusing occurrences to some people, which is why it defaults to false.
.sp
Default:
.B nopassgo
.sp
Recommendation:
.B passgo
.TP
.B tombstone / notombstone
.sp
Print out the tombstone at the end if you get killed.
.sp
This is a useful option to disable when playing on an historically slow terminal.
.sp
Default:
.B tombstone
.sp
Recommendation:
.B tombstone
.TP
.BR inven =style
.sp
Set the inventory style to one of:
.BR overwrite ,
.BR slow ,
or
.BR clear .
.sp
With
.BR overwrite ,
the top lines of the map are overwritten with the list when inventory is requested,
or when "Which item do you wish to ...?" questions are answered with a
.B *
(asterisk).
However, if the list is longer than a screenful, the screen is cleared.
.sp
With
.BR slow ,
lists are displayed one item at a time on the top of the screen.
.sp
With
.BR clear ,
the screen is cleared, the list is displayed, and then the dungeon level is re-displayed.
.sp
Default:
.B clear
.sp
Recommendation:
.B overwrite
.TP
.BR name =rogue-name
.sp
This is the name of your character, as displayed in the rogue score file.
.sp
Default:
.B <<your account name>>
.sp
Recommendation:
.B <<leave as default>>
.TP
.BR fruit =fruit-name
.sp
This should hold the name of a fruit that you enjoy eating.
It is basically a whimsy that rogue uses in a couple of places.
.sp
Default:
.B slime-mold
.sp
Recommendation:
.B apple
.TP
.BR file =rogue-save-path
.sp
The default file name for saving the game.
.sp
Default:
.B ~/.rogue.save
.sp
Recommendation:
.B <<leave as default>>
.TP
.BR score =rogue-score-path
.sp
The path of the rogue score file.
.sp
.B IMPORTANT NOTE:
Changing the rogue score file path without also changing the rogue lock file path is
.B NOT
a good idea.
.sp
Default:
.B ~/.rogue.scr
.sp
Recommendation:
.B <<leave as default>>
.TP
.BR lock =rogue-lock-path
.sp
The rogue lock file used to protect the rogue score file.
.sp
.B IMPORTANT NOTE:
Changing the rogue lock file path without also changing the rogue score file path is
.B NOT
a good idea.
.sp
Default:
.B ~/.rogue.lck
.sp
Recommendation:
.B <<leave as default>>
.SH ENVIRONMENT
The following environment variables affect the execution of
.BR $ROGUEOPTS :
The
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment variable may be used to change the
.B rogue
at startup, rather than having to use the
.B o
command each time you play.
.sp
The
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment variable would be a string that is a series
of comma separated values, with booleans being stated as "name" (true)
or "noname" (false), and strings being "name=....", with the string
being defined up to a comma or the end of the entire option string.
.sp
As an example, here is a recommended
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment value to set in your environment:
.sp
.in +0.5i
export ROGUEOPTS="noterse,flush,jump,seefloor,passgo,tombstone,inven=overwrite,fruit=apple"
.in -0.5i
.PP
If the
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment value is missing or empty, the default options will be used.
Unknown options are silently ignored.
.PP
To assist in the debugging of
.BR rogomatic,
if the name of your character (i.e.,
.BR rogue-name )
starts with
.B rogo\-
when
.B rogue
starts, then the environment variable
.B $ROGOSEED
may be used to set the rogue dungeon number.
.PP
The
.B v
rogue command, in when printing the rogue version, and release date,
also prints the rogue dungeon number.
.PP
.BR NOTE :
Changing the
.B rogue-name
with the
.B o
command does
.B NOT
st in the debugging of
.B rogomatic
as the
.B rogue-name
must be set, via the above mentioned
.B $ROGUEOPTS
environment variable method
.B BEFORE
.BR rogue
starts.
For example:
.sp
.in +0.5i
ROGUEOPTS="name=rogo-bot" ROGOSEED=1227897957 rogue
.in -0.5i
.sp
See the
.BR rogomatic (6)
man page for how rogue dungeon seed debugging is performed by
.BR rogomatic .
.SH FILES
.TP
.BR Lock\ File \ \-\ @LOCKFILE@
.sp
The rogue lock file is a zero-length file that must be writable by the user.
It is used to help prevent multiple processes on the local machine from
writing to the rogue score file at the same time.
.sp
If the rogue lock file does not exist, the lock file will be created when
updating the rogue score file.
.TP
.BR Save\ file \ \-\ @SAVEFILE@
.sp
The rogue save file is created whenever you use the
.B S
command to save the game, or if certain signals are successfully caught and
the "auto save" action is successfully completed.
.sp
A rogue save file is likely, but is not guaranteed to restore in a different system.
Among the diverse reasons a restore on a different system might fail are
CPU architecture differences, and the whim of the C compiler.
.sp
If the rogue save file does not exist, it will be created when a game is saved.
.TP
.BR Score\ File \ \-\ @SCOREFILE@
.sp
The rogue score file contains the top rogue games, in terms of gold collected.
By default, 10 rogue score are saved.
.sp
The rogue score file must be writable by the user.
.sp
The length of the rogue score file is usually 112 bytes per score slot, so the default
rogue score file size is 1120 bytes.
.sp
Unlike the BSD rogue game on the Vax, rogue keeps track of top rogue scores,
no matter how they were played, and no matter if they won the game or not.
.sp
If the rogue score file does not exist,
.B rogue
will create it.
.sp
If the rogue score file is corrupted, or the format is too old, then
an error message will be displayed advising that the rogue score file be removed.
.sp
If you enter into
.B wizard mode
at any time during the game,
then your score will
.B NOT
be recorded in the rogue score file,
even if you turn off
.B wizard mode
during the game.
.SH SOURCE CODE
The source code for rogue version 5.4.5 is available at:
.PP
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4
.in -0.5i
.PP
in the form of a GitHub repo.
.PP
The above GitHub repo is maintained by:
.B Landon\ Curt\ Noll
(GitHub user @lcn2:
.IR https://github.com/lcn2 ).
.PP
The port to ISO C 2017 with GNU extensions, the port to various platforms
such as NetBSD, Linux, and Cygwin, and many rogue bug fixes applied to
rogue version 5.4.5 were made by Landon Curt Noll (chongo), and Anthony
C Howe (SirWumpus).
.PP
.BR BONUS :
The historic
.B wizard mode password
may be found in a source code comment about a defined symbol
in the \fIrogue.h\fP header file.
In other words,
as the expression goes:
.B RTFS
(\fIhttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RTFS\fP) :-).
.PP
For more information on
.BR wizard\ mode ,
see the
.B wizard mode
spoiler text at:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.I github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#wizard-mode-spoilers
.in -0.5i
.SH VERSION 5.4.5
.PP
The rogue version was changed from 5.4.4 to 5.4.5
to help distinguish this code from various buggy 5.4.4 code.
.PP
Rogue version 5.4.5 plays like the original Vax binary that was distributed on the BSD 4.3 Reno tapes.
.PP
In addition to a port to ISO C 2017 with GNU extensions, this version contains a fair number
of significant bug fixes to help avoid the game crashing.
.PP
For a general overview of code improvements, see:
.sp
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#why-yet-another-rouge-repo
.in -0.5i
.PP
.B IMPORTANT\ NOTE :
This code is
.B NOT the so-called "\fIPublic domain rogue\fP" rogue game that distributions such as NetBSD imported from 386BSD.
That "\fIPublic domain rogue\fP" was an attempt to reverse engineer the original game found on
the BSD distribution tapes, and as such the game play differs from the original game in a number of ways.
Rogue version 5.4.5, thankfully, is
.B NOT
compatible with the NetBSD rogue.
.SH SEE ALSO
We recommend that you read the
.B README.md
file of the above mentioned GitHub repo:
.PP
.in +0.5i
.I https://github.com/lcn2/rogue5.4#rogue-54
.in -0.5i
.PP
The so-called "\fBspoiler section\fP", found in the lower section of
the above URL may be useful for people who wish to learn how to
play the game.
It contains game details that have been derived from the source code.
.PP
For additional details read:
.I "A guide to the Dungeons of Doom"
by Michael C. Toy, and Kenneth C. R. C. Arnold.
.PP
See the
.B rogue.doc
file for a copy of that guide.
.SH AUTHORS
Michael C. Toy,
